application_type_full: Tree works: Trees in conservation areas/subject to TPOs
description:
T 393 -Cherry- as per map-Wound from past failure. Decayed stem. Potential habitat value-Cut to leave 3 m height stand stump.
T 395- Pendunculate oak-Extensive storm damage.  Tear- out wounds and cavities in crown with high likely ecological value. Bark on stem is largely dead and dysfunctional with scars from past fruiting body attachment. Hazard of crown/ whole tree failure. Good lower crown vitality.- Reduce crown height and spread by approx. 4 meters
T 397 Red Horse Chestnut-Principal dead and fractured stem. Wide spreading stems to south are highly vulnerable. tree cannot be reasonably retained. Remove to 2 m stump.
T398- Damson- Dead,  partially collapsed tree. Foreseeable failure hazard,- Remove.
T 503- Elder-Dead. Leaning over BBQ area- remove
T 504- Box Elder- Large Near dead tree with  fracture wounds and major stems overhanging path adjacent. Young growth developing gives potential scope for pruning.- Cut to 4m height live crown framework, retaining low growth.
T 510- Red Oak- Past heavy crown reduction. Large dead wood over bus stop- remove dead wood.
T 511- Horse Chestnut- Located off-site in property adjacent. Low vitality with early defoliation, likely to be caused by repeated and excessive horse chestnut leaf miner. Long over-extended lateral branch bon south west side overhanging the site has significant wound at 9m and is vulnerable. The same branch has a wound at 11m from past failure.- reduce long over extended stem on south west side ( with wound at 9m) by 4-5m.
